.TH "lease" "1" "May 26, 2026" "Version 1.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
\f[B]lease\f[R] \- FIFO semaphore utility that manages resource
ownership by processes.
.SH SYNOPSIS
\f[B]lease\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]]...
.PP
\f[B]lease\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]]...
\-\- command [\f[I]arguments\&...\f[R]]...
.SH DESCRIPTION
FIFO semaphore utility that manages resource ownership by processes.
.PP
Obtains a lease/ownership for the specified resource.
When the resource lease is requested for a specific PID, it succeeds if
the resource is available, otherwise, it will add the requesting process
to a FIFO queue and block until the resource becomes available when the
other processes that acquired the resource earlier release it or finish
executing.
.PP
A process can borrow a resource either for itself or for another process
by supplying \f[B]\-p PID\f[R].
.PP
This utility can also launch a user\-supplied command upon successful
acquisition of this resource lease.
In this case, option \f[B]\-p\f[R] is not needed and \f[B]\-r\f[R] is
optional and will be calculated, if not specified, by hashing the user
command, thus using the user command as a resource identifier.
.PP
A resource can be explicitly released with the \f[B]\-\-release\f[R]
option.
Otherwise the resource will be released when the owner process ends.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
\f[B]\-r {resource} | \-\-resource={resource}\f[R]
Resource identifier.
Lease/ownership is created/acquired on this resource.
.TP
\f[B]\-p {PID} | \-\-pid={PID}\f[R]
Process ID that is to become an owner of the resource (to acquire a
lease on it).
.TP
\f[B]\-d {directory} | \-\-dir={directory}\f[R]
A directory where the semaphore/resource/queue files are stored.
Defaults to XDG_RUNTIME_DIR/zemaphore if present, falling back to
XDG_DATA_HOME/.local/share/zemaphore when systemd is not present.
.TP
\f[B]\-c {number} | \-\-concurrency={number}\f[R]
Maximum number of processes allowed to own/lease the resource at the
same time and run concurrently.
.TP
\f[B]\f[R]
Concurrency is enforced within the same concurrency/exclusivity group.
Minimum of 1 is enforced.
Default is 1.
.TP
\f[B]\-x {group} | \-\-exclusivity={group}\f[R]
Exclusivity group code/identifier.
\f[B]\f[R]
Only processes within one group can be executed concurrently.
Concurrency defines the maximum number of processes that can run in
parallel within the same group.
\f[B]\f[R]
If a resource lease is acquired by Group A then a request from Group B
will block until all processes in Group A scheduled before have
completed and released this resource.
\f[B]\f[R]
Optional, defaults to \f[B]X\f[R]
.TP
\f[B]\-w {wait sec} | \-\-wait={wait sec}\f[R]
Wait this long (seconds) before giving up on locking/acquiring the
resource.
.TP
\f[B]\f[R]
When wait time exceeds this parameter, the semaphore exits with
non\-zero code.
The script keeps waiting if there are too many other processes
requesting this resource.
.TP
\f[B]\f[R]
Requestors are placed in the queue to wait and get their leases as they
become available in FIFO order.
.TP
\f[B]\f[R]
Defaults to infinite wait.
.TP
\f[B]\-i {interval sec} | \-\-interval={interval sec}\f[R]
While waiting for the resource to be released, the script wakes up
periodically to check whether the resource was released or the previous
owner ceased to exist.
This is a polling/wake\-up interval.
Fractional numbers are allowed.
.TP
\f[B]\f[R]
Optional.
The default is automatically derived from the wait time.
.TP
\f[B]\-k {second} | \-\-kill={second}\f[R]
If another process that owns this resource is \(lqstuck\(rq, becomes a
zombie, or simply has been around for this many seconds, then TERM it.
By default no killing is performed.
Fractional numbers are allowed.
.TP
\f[B]\f[R]
This parameter also supports extended format
\f[B]seconds[=SIGNAL][;seconds[=SIGNAL][;\&...]]\f[R].
For example, parameter \f[B]\(lq\-k
300:310:400=INT:410:500=HUP:600=KILL\(rq\f[R] will send \f[B]TERM\f[R]
after 300 and 310 seconds, send \f[B]INT\f[R] at 400 and 410 seconds,
send \f[B]HUP\f[R] at 500 seconds, send \f[B]KILL\f[R] at 600 seconds.
.TP
\f[B]\-e {second} | \-\-expire={second}\f[R]
Resource will be considered automatically unlocked when the lease time
exceeds this number of seconds.
The lease gets invalidated and the resource/lease record is purged
afterward.
.TP
\f[B]\-R | \-\-release\f[R]
Makes an attempt to release a previously obtained/leased resource for
the resource/PID combination.
Semaphore is more efficient when it is released explicitly.
Doing so sends instant notification signals to other semaphores waiting
for this resource to become available.
Otherwise it relies on periodic polling and may wait for as long as
specified with \f[B]\-i\f[R] before checking whether the resource became
available.
.TP
\f[B]\-\-sweep\f[R]
Purge empty queues/resources.
With \f[B]\-v\f[R], also lists the existing queues and statistics.
.TP
\f[B]\-v | \-\-verbose\f[R]
Be verbose, think out loud.
Can be specified multiple times to increase verbosity level.
.TP
\f[B]\-h | \-\-help\f[R]
Print this help.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Acquire resource lease with concurrency limit
\f[B]\f[R]
.IP
.EX
lease \-r \(aqXYZ\(aq \-p $PPID \-c 2 \-i 30 \-k 240 \-w 600
.EE
.PP
Asks for a lock on resource \f[B]XYZ\f[R] for the caller shell parent
process, allowing one more resource owner (have 2 owners) to have the
lock at the same time.
.PP
If the resource is unavailable, it re\-checks every 30 seconds.
.PP
Attempts to TERM other processes that held the lock for over 240
seconds.
.PP
Gives up after 10 minutes of waiting.
.SS Escalating signal sequence
\f[B]\f[R]
.IP
.EX
lease \-r \(aqXYZ\(aq \-p \(dq$(ps \-p $$ \-o ppid:1=)\(dq \-c 2 \-i 30 \-k 240:250:260=HUP:270=INT \-w 600
.EE
.PP
Same as the example above, except that if another lease does not become
available, it attempts sending signals to the lease owner:
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]TERM\f[R] at 240 and 250 seconds
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]HUP\f[R] at 260 seconds
.IP \(bu 2
\f[B]INT\f[R] at 270 seconds
.SS Expiring stale leases
\f[B]\f[R]
.IP
.EX
lease \-r \(aqXYZ\(aq \-p \(dq$$\(dq \-i 30 \-e 240 \-w 600 || exit 1
.EE
.PP
Attempts to lock resource \f[B]XYZ\f[R] for the calling shell.
.PP
Checks availability every 30 seconds while waiting.
.PP
If the lock is not available after 10 minutes (600 seconds), exits the
calling shell script.
.PP
While waiting, invalidates existing leases older than 240 seconds.
.PP
Keep in mind that invalidating a lease does not necessarily make the
resource immediately eligible to be locked, because there may be other
semaphores already waiting in the FIFO queue.
